  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3655558791" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3655558791" />
    <a title="Marc Gerstein" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15102294-marc-gerstein"><img alt="Marc Gerstein" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1389185056p2/15102294.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3655558791?book_show_action=true">Dec 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marc Gerstein" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marc Gerstein" href="/user/show/15102294-marc-gerstein">Marc Gerstein</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15102294-marc-gerstein?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3655558791" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4102696272336285226">Romain Gary, the notable French writer, diplomat and Wold War iI hero definitely deserves to have his life be the subject of a fictional autobiography, which is what <i>Promise At Dawn</i> written shortly before his 1980 suicide, is. It’s not clear why he took his life; a suicide note specifically denied it was related to the recent suicide of his second wife. I don’t know. <i>Promise At Dawn</i> stops way before that, at the end of WWII in 1945.<br/><br/>The focus of the work is Gary’s mother, a single mother who was </span>
  <span id="freeText4102696272336285226" style="display:none">Romain Gary, the notable French writer, diplomat and Wold War iI hero definitely deserves to have his life be the subject of a fictional autobiography, which is what <i>Promise At Dawn</i> written shortly before his 1980 suicide, is. It’s not clear why he took his life; a suicide note specifically denied it was related to the recent suicide of his second wife. I don’t know. <i>Promise At Dawn</i> stops way before that, at the end of WWII in 1945.<br /><br />The focus of the work is Gary’s mother, a single mother who was a middling stage performer in Russia and eventually made her way, with her son through Poland and on to France. As an elevator pitch, this mother-son chronicle sounds about as interesting as thumbing through a six-year old copy of National Geographic while sitting in the waiting room outside a shrink’s office. Z-z-z-z-z-z. But this is no ordinary mother-son story. And that’s coming from one who knows (and grew up with) a “Jewish mother” and even laughed my way through <i>Portnoy’s Complaint</i>, an iconic fictional mother-son thing, who, being married to a Chinese woman, engage in countless debates and arguments over the “Tiger Mother” so-called ideal, and who, among my cringe-TV guilty pleasures, joyfully sneered at TLC’s <i>I Love A Mama’s Boy</i>. <br /><br />The mother-son dynamic here is on a completely different level. You can describe it as dysfunctional, loving, constructive, emotionally abusive, heroic . . . be right in each respect. Freud was born too early. He should have had a chance to digest <i>Promise At Dawn</i> before formulating his oedipal theories. The story is a must read. <br /><br />That said, be warned about the writing style. It’s very — overly I’d say — flowery and meandering with what I see as pretensions to profoundness that actually detract from what I think readers would feel had Gary simply wrote it straight and let the story speak for itself. And I don’t think I’m being overly snarky saying it. Gary owned up to such writing tendencies summing up the rejections his initial story submissions garnered as follows:<br /><blockquote><br />For six months not one of my works saw the light of day. They were considered “too literary.” At the time I did not understand what was happening to me, but now I do. Encouraged by my first success, I let myself be carried away by my devouring need to catch the last ball no matter what the cost, to go to the bottom of the problem at a single stroke of the pen; and, since the problem had no bottom or, if it had, my arm was not long enough to reach it . . . . It took me a long time to admit that the reader was entitled to a certain amount of consideration and that it was necessary to explain to him, as to every newcomer at the Hôtel-Pension Mermonts, the number of his room, the way the switches worked, to give him his key and indicate where he would find all the necessities.<br /></blockquote><br />Even after getting his first story published, her ran into another slew of rejections.<br /><blockquote><br />My race against time was assuming a desperate character, and it showed in my writing. In my determination to write a fabulous masterpiece which should leave the world open-mouthed with admiration, I forced my voice beyond its range, so that it became strident and unpleasant. Aiming at greatness, I achieved only pretentiousness; standing on tiptoe in an attempt to reveal my stature for all to see, I succeeded only in uncovering my lack of it; determined to be a genius, I merely made more clearly visible the limits of my talent.<br /></blockquote><br />Finally, he completed his first novel <i>A European Education</i>, which he wrote while on active duty as a de Gaulle-inspired Free French flier fighting the Nazis. It was accepted for publication. And it became a hit. And it was followed by, many many more works. So it seems reasonable to assume Gary put his literary pretentiousness to rest. (I’m anxious to tackle <i>European education</i> and find out.) I’m guessing, though, that when Gary turned, late in life, to this extremely personal fictional autobiography, the pretentiousness that dogged his early efforts came roaring back, because in my opinion, the above two Gary characterizations of his early efforts are all over the place in . The strength of the story and the characterization of the mother make this well worth reading. But if you do find yourself rolling your eyes when it comes to his pseudo-literary flourishes, just go with it and know that the story itself will ultimately overwhelm the fluff.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4102696272336285226" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


