  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3255510652?book_show_action=true">Apr 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andreea" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andreea" href="/user/show/2219555-andreea">Andreea</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback " href="/book/show/119003.La_promesse_de_l_aube">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2219555-andreea?shelf=2020">2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3255510652" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13189915479238032397">When I started this book I told everyone who listen that from the first pages this would be a 5 star read for me. And then I got to the second part and then the third. The magic I felt reading about Gary’s childhood, the humor, the innocence, the heartwarming relationship with his mother, and his desire to please her, turned into some question marks as I progressed with the reading. It was still good writing, still funny here and there, but I felt the relationship became a bit... toxic (?). It w</span>
  <span id="freeText13189915479238032397" style="display:none">When I started this book I told everyone who listen that from the first pages this would be a 5 star read for me. And then I got to the second part and then the third. The magic I felt reading about Gary’s childhood, the humor, the innocence, the heartwarming relationship with his mother, and his desire to please her, turned into some question marks as I progressed with the reading. It was still good writing, still funny here and there, but I felt the relationship became a bit... toxic (?). It was strange to see or hear his mother at every step of his life and worst of all him lying to her under the pretext that he was protecting her feelings. There are a lot of things to analyse in this relationship and even if during the war it may have been a lifeline, still it’s strange to have your mother haunt you like this. Or maybe it was all for literature purposes.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13189915479238032397" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


