<div id="review_3006688201" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3006688201" />
    <a title="Tom Stamper" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24682440-tom-stamper"><img alt="Tom Stamper" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1471402186p2/24682440.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3006688201?book_show_action=true">Oct 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom Stamper" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom Stamper" href="/user/show/24682440-tom-stamper">Tom Stamper</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24682440-tom-stamper?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24682440-tom-stamper?shelf=world-fiction">world-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3006688201" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9345529619030991958">The book didn’t really work for me at the beginning. It felt over-written and I wondered if it was the fault of the author or the translator. After a few chapters it seemed to settle down or I got use to the flowery language. It’s a story of humble beginnings that explain the accomplishments and at times great failures. He’s the only son of a single mother who is determined to make him a famous French diplomat despite the fact they live in Poland and do not speak French. In so many ways this is </span>
  <span id="freeText9345529619030991958" style="display:none">The book didn’t really work for me at the beginning. It felt over-written and I wondered if it was the fault of the author or the translator. After a few chapters it seemed to settle down or I got use to the flowery language. It’s a story of humble beginnings that explain the accomplishments and at times great failures. He’s the only son of a single mother who is determined to make him a famous French diplomat despite the fact they live in Poland and do not speak French. In so many ways this is a tribute to his mother and likely the primary reason for his writing it. The word co-dependence comes to mind.<br /><br />I kept reading because Gary is suspenseful. He won’t hint at whether next obstacle is agony or ecstasy but you know it’s going to be big and worth reading. Ping Pong Champion, World War II bomber for the French resistance decorated by DeGaulle, and published author before the age of 25. <br />Coming into the book we know Romain Gary is going to be a famous writer and diplomat that marries Jean Seberg and challenges Clint Eastwood to a duel. That sitting in my head made each suspense more worthwhile. I came to the end and I still don’t quite understand how he did it. This is probably because his humility makes his accomplishments seem like luck although that’s hard to believe. What it also means for the reader is that it’s a rare rags-to-riches story that offers no path or guidance to reader for how to find success. <br /><br />But the strangest thing about the book is why a guy who overcame so much would one day kill himself. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9345529619030991958" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


